defaultCycling: the way ahead
default doesn’t mention the disabled at all, and talks about the elderly only in passing, but I want now to introduce to you some evidence from 
defaultPor
defaulttland, Oregon.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Cycling Coordinator there, a chap called Roge
defaultr Geller, has written a famous paper entitled 
defaultFour types of cyclist
default. The four types are:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe strong and fearless make up about 1% of the population, and will cycle regardless of 
defaultthe conditions. 
default(
defaultOr rather, they are more concerned about potholes than heavy traffic.
default)
default&#xa0;
defaultThe enthused and confident make up about 8-10% of the population, and they include people like myself.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe interested but concerned make up about 60% of the population. In high cycling countries, th
defaulte authorities have found that it has paid off
default to 
defaultensure t
defaulthat this group is properly 
defaultprovide
defaultd
default for. Thus we see the development of protected cycleways and the like. Cities like Cambridge, certainly, and York, probably, are now in a position where they can seriously consider the provision of quality infrastructure 
defaultat a strategic level, but cities like London and Manchester don’t even 
defaulthave the basics in place just
default yet
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe exemplar schemes which are proposed for London and Manchester are all to the good, of course, but only up to a point. 
defaultTo begin with, Lynn Sloman 
defaulthas suggested, the focus of our attention should switch from a few grandiose schemes to thousands of small initiatives. "Even if their impact is not massive,"
default&#xa0;
defaultCycling: the way ahead
